{{Italic title}} {{Infobox book | italic title = | name = ''How to Break a Terrorist: The US Interrogators Who Used Brains, Not Brutality, to Take Down the Deadliest Man in Iraq'' | image = File:How_to_break_a_terrorist_book_cover.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | author = Matthew Alexander ([[pseudonym]]) | audio_read_by = | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | release_number = | subject = | genre = | set_in = | published = | publisher = St. Martin's Griffin | publisher2 = | pub_date = | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 304 | awards = | isbn = 9780312675110 | isbn_note = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }}
'''''How to Break a Terrorist: The US Interrogators Who Used Brains, Not Brutality, to Take Down the Deadliest Man in Iraq''''' is a book written by an American [[airman]] who played a key role in tracking down [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]].<ref name=DN> {{cite news |url = http://i4.democracynow.org/2008/12/3/us_interrogator_in_iraq_says_torture |title = US Interrogator in Iraq Says Torture Policy Has Led to Deaths of Thousands of American Soldiers |publisher = [[Democracy Now]] |author = |date = 2008-12-04 |accessdate = 2008-12-04 |quote = |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fi4.democracynow.org%2F2008%2F12%2F3%2Fus_interrogator_in_iraq_says_torture&date=2008-12-04 |archivedate = 2008-12-04 |df = }} </ref><ref name=WashingtonPost2008-12-04> {{cite news |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/11/28/AR2008112802242_pf.html |title = I'm Still Tortured by What I Saw in Iraq |publisher = [[Washington Post]] |author = [[Matthew Alexander (writer)|Matthew Alexander]] |date = 2008-11-30 |accessdate = 2008-12-04 |quote = |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fwp-dyn%2Fcontent%2Farticle%2F2008%2F11%2F28%2FAR2008112802242_pf.html&date=2008-12-04 |archivedate = 2008-12-04 |df = }} </ref><ref name=Fox> {{cite news |url = http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C460944%2C00.html |title = Book Details How U.S. Forces Brought Down al-Zarqawi |publisher = [[Fox News]] |author = |date = 2008-12-03 |accessdate = 2008-12-04 |quote = |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.foxnews.com%2Fstory%2F0%2C2933%2C460944%2C00.html&date=2008-12-04 |archivedate = 2008-12-04 |df = }} </ref><ref name=MiddleEastOnline> {{cite news |url = http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=29064 |title = Torture blamed for US deaths in Iraq |publisher = [[Middle East Online]] |author = |date = 2008-12-04 |accessdate = 2008-12-04 |quote = |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.middle-east-online.com%2Fenglish%2F%3Fid%3D29064&date=2008-12-04 |archivedate = 2008-12-04 |df = }} </ref>
==Background==
The interrogator who wrote the book published it under the [[pen name]] Matthew Alexander, for security reasons.<ref name=WashingtonPost2008-12-04/><ref name=Time2008-12-02>. {{cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1863053,00.html | title=How to Break a Terrorist | publisher=[[Time magazine]] | author=[[Gilbert Cruz]] | date=2008-12-02 | accessdate=2008-12-05 | quote= }} </ref><ref name=TheRawStory>
{{cite news |url = http://rawstory.com/news/2008/Former_interrogator_speaks_out_against_torture_1204.html |title = Brains, not brutality needed, former interrogator argues |publisher = [[The Raw Story]] |author = David Edwards, [[Muriel Kane]] |date = 2008-12-04 |accessdate = 2008-12-05 |quote = |archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Frawstory.com%2Fnews%2F2008%2FFormer_interrogator_speaks_out_against_torture_1204.html&date=2008-12-05 |archivedate = 2008-12-05 |deadurl = yes |df = }} </ref> The author wrote the book as a pseudonymous officer in the [[US Air Force]] who had served for fourteen years. Alexander's real name has been sealed by court order by the [[District of Columbia District Court]].<ref>{{cite court |litigants = Alexander versus Department of Defense |vol = |reporter = |opinion = Rosemary M. Collyer |pinpoint = |court = [[District Of Columbia District Court]] |date = September 18, 2008 |url= http://dockets.justia.com/docket/court-dcdce/case_no-1:2008cv01606/case_id-133150/}}</ref> Alexander makes television appearances under his pseudonym. According to [[Jeff Stein (author)|Jeff Stein]], writing in the ''[[Washington Post]]'', the author's real name was [[Anthony Camerino]], a Major in the [[United States Air Force Reserve]].<ref name=WashingtonPost2011-02-01>. {{cite news | url = http://voices.washingtonpost.com/spy-talk/2011/02/matthew_alexander_half_of_spec.html | title = Ex-interrogator describes mistaken Iraq raids | publisher = [[Washington Post]] | author = [[Jeff Stein (author)|Jeff Stein]] | date = 2011-02-01 | accessdate = 2012-08-06 | quote = Matthew Alexander, the pen name for Air Force Reserve Maj. Anthony Camerino, describes his struggle to provide compensation for the victims of the raids in a new book, "Kill or Capture: How a Special Operations Task Force Took Down a Notorious Al Qaeda Terrorist," to be published today. }}</ref> In an [[op-ed]] published in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' he wrote that after his arrival in Iraq in 2006 he found:<ref name=WashingtonPost2008-12-04/>
{{quote|The Army was still conducting interrogations according to the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp|Guantanamo Bay model]]: Interrogators were nominally using the methods outlined in the [[U.S. Army Interrogation Field Manual|U.S. Army Field Manual]], the interrogators' bible, but they were pushing in every way possible to bend the rules -- and often break them.<ref name=WashingtonPost2008-12-04/>}}
The author has stated that when [[the Pentagon]] vetted the book they initially made 93 [[redaction]]s.<ref name=MiddleEastOnline/>
{{quote|I sued the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] first to review the book and then to argue the redactions, because they had redacted obvious [[unclassified]] material, things that I had taken straight out of the unclassified field manual and also some items that were directly off the Army's own website. So, eventually they acquiesced on eighty of the ninety-three redactions.}}
Alexander is an outspoken opponent of [[torture]].<ref>[http://howtobreakaterrorist.blogspot.com/ Terrorist Breaker Blog]</ref> He refutes the [[effectiveness of torture]], citing its negative long-term effects such as recruiting for Al-Qaeda. He also argues that torture is contrary to the American principles of freedom, liberty, and justice, and that should they resort to torture, American interrogators become the enemy they serve to defeat. Similar arguments have been made by other former interrogators from the [[U.S. military]], [[FBI]], and the [[CIA]], including Colonel [[Steven Kleinman]].<ref>[http://niemanwatchdog.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=Background.view&backgroundid=272 Abuse Has No Place in Interrogation Policy, Nieman Watchdog Group Commentary, July 29th, 2008]</ref> In an interview with human rights lawyer [[Scott Horton (lawyer)|Scott Horton]] for [[Harper's Magazine]], Alexander said
{{quote|The American public has a right to know that they do not have to choose between torture and terror. There is a better way to conduct interrogations that works more efficiently, keeps Americans safe, and doesn't sacrifice our integrity. Our greatest victory to date in this war, the death of [[Abu Musab Al Zarqawi]] (which saved thousands of lives and helped pave the way to the [[Sunni Awakening]]), was achieved using interrogation methods that had nothing to do with torture. The American people deserve to know that.<ref name=harpers>[http://harpers.org/archive/2008/12/hbc-90004036 Six questions for Matthew Alexander, author of How to Break a Terrorist]</ref>}}
Alexander described [[Marc Thiessen]]'s 2010 book ''Courting Disaster'', which defended the use of [[enhanced interrogation techniques]], as 'a literary defense of war criminals'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2246692/pagenum/all/|title=Courting Fear|first=Matthew|last=Alexander|authorlink=|publisher=''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]''|date=February 27, 2010}}</ref>
